    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kind of confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but it feels like the principal balance barely moves. can you explain how the interest calculation works on a declining balance so i can understand why it seems like so little is going toward the actual loan?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, and it's actually a great example of how compound interest works in your favor (or against you, depending on your perspective). When you make a payment, a tiny portion goes toward interest—the cost of borrowing money for that month—while the vast majority is technically \"going toward\" principal, but the interest eats up most of the payment amount until the balance gets very small.\n\nThink of it like a giant mountain of debt where you are slowly chipping away at the top; early on, the \"interest tax\" is so high that your hard-earned dollars are mostly paying that tax rather than reducing the actual mountain. However, as your balance decreases, the interest portion shrinks, and eventually, you'll notice your payments start hitting the principal much harder.\n\nTo help visualize this, imagine a small, fast-moving river (your loan balance) flowing into a massive, stagnant lake (the interest calculation). In the beginning, the lake is huge, so even if you pour in a bucket of water (your payment), most of it gets absorbed into the lake's volume before it can lower the water level. Only when the lake gets smaller does your bucket make a noticeable difference in the depth.\n\nIf",
      "source": "target",
